If you'd like to provide a direct download link using the `download` attribute of an `a` tag, you can do so without changing much of the server-side code. The `download` attribute only requires the correct URL to the resource and the desired filename when the resource is downloaded.

Firstly, let's modify the `addFile` function on the client side to include the `download` attribute within the generated `a` tag. You may also choose to display a friendly message or the original filename as the link text, rather than the URL. Here's how you'd change the `addFile` function after the JSON message from the server includes the proper file URL and original filename:

```javascript
function addFile(sender, originalName, fileUrl) {
    const fileLinksDiv = document.getElementById('file-links');
    const fileLink = document.createElement('a');
    fileLink.href = fileUrl;
    fileLink.download = originalName;  // Set the proposed download filename.
    fileLink.innerText = sender + ' uploaded a file: ' + originalName;
    fileLinksDiv.appendChild(fileLink);
    fileLinksDiv.appendChild(document.createElement('br'));
}
```

With this client-side change, when users click on the link, their browser will download the file with the specified `originalName` as the filename. 

In your provided server code, the `broadcast` function is necessary because it sends a message to all connected WebSocket clients about the new file upload, including the URL for the file and the original filename. It seems from your request that you want to keep this functionality but ensure that the provided download link uses the `download` attribute on the client-side, which I've provided above.

Remember, if you are serving files from the server, you should ensure that your HTTP server code includes the correct Content-Disposition header for the downloading part. However, since we are using the `download` attribute on the `a` tag on the client-side, and the `application/octet-stream` Content-Type will often prompt the browser to download files, this is not critical.

Please note, your current server code generates unique filenames for each file to avoid conflicts, so even if we use the `download` attribute to give the downloaded file the original name, the file stored on the server will still have a unique UUID-based name. If you want to maintain the original filenames on the server as well, you would need to handle potential conflicts from files with the same name.

You should make sure to maintain security by validating the file types and content being uploaded to avoid any security vulnerabilities due to user-uploaded content.

